# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] The **AAAS David and Betty Hamburg Award for Science Diplomacy** (2022–), formerly the **AAAS Award for Science Diplomacy** (2010–2021) and **Award for International Scientific Cooperation** (1992–2009), is awarded by the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] After the 2021 presentation, the award was renamed in honor of psychiatrists David A.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] The award offers a monetary prize of $2,500, a certificate of citation, and travel expenses to attend the AAAS annual meeting to receive the award.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-award-for-scientific-freedom-and-responsibility] The establishment of this new Award for Scientific Freedom and Responsibility was announced by AAAS executive officer William D.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-award-for-scientific-freedom-and-responsibility] The award, presented for the first time at the 1982 AAAS Annual Meeting in Washington, DC, consisted of a plaque and a cash prize of $1,000.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize] The prize is named after nuclear physicist Philip Abelson.The award consists of an engraved medallion and an honorarium of $5,000.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The **Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University**, formerly the **Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia**, is the oldest natural science research institution and museum in the Americas.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was founded in 1812, by many of the leading naturalists of the young American republic with an expressed mission of "the encouragement and cultivation of the sciences".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It has sponsored expeditions, conducted original environmental and systematics research, and amassed natural history collections containing more than 17 million specimens.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy also organizes public exhibits and educational programs for both schools and the general public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] During the first decades of the United States, Philadelphia was the cultural capital and one of the country's commercial centers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the city's institutions, the Library Company and the American Philosophical Society, were centers of enlightened thought and scientific inquiry.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The increasing sophistication of the earth and life sciences, combined with a growing awareness of the variety of life and landscape in the American wilderness, led a small group of naturalists to establish the Academy of Natural Sciences in the winter of 1812.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The academy was meant to foster a gathering of fellow naturalists and to nurture the growth and credibility of American science.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] They frequently looked to their European counterparts for inspiration and expertise and longed to be regarded as equals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] On 25 April 1817 they were incorporated into the society under the title of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia by the legislature of Pennsylvania.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1 January 1818, eight members were published.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2011, the Academy became affiliated with nearby Drexel University and changed its name to the Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Within a decade of its founding, the Academy became the undisputed center of natural sciences in the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy members were frequently enlisted to participate in national surveys of the western territories and other major expeditions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Thomas Jefferson of Virginia, John Edwards Holbrook of South Carolina, Thomas Nuttall and Richard Owen of the United Kingdom, Georges Cuvier of France, and Alexander von Humboldt of Prussia were among the corresponding members (members who lived far from Philadelphia) of the Academy's first decades.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later during the 19th century, other notable naturalists and scientists, including John James Audubon, Charles S.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, John Cassin, Edward Drinker Cope, Ezra Townsend Cresson, Richard Harlan, Ferdinand V.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, John Lawrence LeConte, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, George Ord, and James Rehn were members.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Corresponding members included Charles Darwin along with his supporters Asa Gray, and Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] For much of its history, new members had to be nominated by two current members and then elected by the remaining members.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These requirements were dropped in 1924.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable 20th-century scientists include James Böhlke, James Bond, Henry Weed Fowler, Ruth Patrick, Henry Pilsbry, H.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy of Natural Sciences holds an internationally important natural history collection.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, there are over 18 million biological specimens, and hundreds of thousands of volumes, journals, illustrations, photographs, and archival items in its library.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These collections were obtained through multiple means, including the donation or purchase of existing collections or individual items, the collection activities of Academy-sponsored expeditions, or those of individual scientists, whether or not they work at the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some collections were originally gathered by other institutions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a number of the natural history collections at the American Philosophical Society were relocated to the Academy by the end of the 19th century.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Traditionally, researchers at natural science (or natural history) institutions such as the Academy engaged in biological taxonomy, the science of discovering, describing, naming, and classifying species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, research has shifted in emphasis to the science of systematics, the study of the evolutionary relationships among these species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy preserves many type specimens, the reference material that helps establish a species' identity.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] They also preserve additional specimens with which scientists can investigate the nature of these species, their relationships with other species, their evolutionary history, or their conservation status.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's collections include a wide range of specimens across the tree of life.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also maintains several historically important collections.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Botany is study of plants, including nonvascular bryophytes (mosses, liverworts, and hornworts) and vascular plants, including ferns, conifers and flowering plants.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The field of botany has also traditionally included the study of algae, lichens, and fungi which are now classified in different biological kingdoms.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Collections at the Academy, which are housed in the Philadelphia Herbarium (PH), the oldest institutional herbarium in the New World, include some of the oldest and most important botanical collections in the Americas.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable early collectors include Benjamin Smith Barton, Constatine Rafinesque, Thomas Meehan, Thomas Nuttall, and Fredrick Pursh.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains approximately 1.5 million specimens of vascular plants, fungi, lichens, algae, and fossil plants, 40,000 of which are types.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also contains some special collections, including the plants collected by Johann and Georg Forster during the voyages of Captain James Cook, and by Meriwether Lewis during the Lewis and Clark expedition (Corps of Discovery).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department's current focus is plant biodiversity and evolution focusing on Apocynaceae (milkweed or dogbane family) and Polygalaceae.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's Diatom Herbarium, the largest in the Americas and the second largest in the world, contains approximately 220,000 slides of these microscopic algae.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains many specimens contributed by notable collectors, a diversity of fossil diatoms, and diatoms collected as part of numerous freshwater environmental surveys in the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Diatom Herbarium also provides collections and taxonomic services for the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Former curators of note include Charles S.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, Ruth Patrick, and Charles Reimer.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Entomology has been important to the Academy since its founding.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of its earliest members include Thomas Say, regarded as the father of American entomology, and Titian Peale, a leading natural history illustrator and the chief naturalist on the United States Exploring Expedition (1834–1842).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The entomology collection currently contains more than 3.5 million specimens and includes the Titian Peale Moth and Butterfly Collection, the oldest entomology collection in the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, Daniel Otte, an expert on Orthoptera (crickets, grasshoppers, and their relatives) is a pioneer of presenting biological data on the internet through the creation of the Orthoptera Species File.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator and Entomology Department Chair, Jon Gelhaus is a leading expert on crane flies and manages the Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Ichthyology has also been a part of Academy collections and research since its beginnings, but the size of the collection was relatively modest until acquisition of Edward Drinker Cope's personal collections in 1898.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] A few years later, Henry Weed Fowler began his tenure at the Academy, during which he systematized the collections and described 1,408 species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke, William Saul, and William Smith-Vaniz are among the scientists who followed Fowler.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, John Lundberg, an expert in catfishes, pioneered deep channel collecting in large tropical rivers and is the lead author of a seminal scientific paper on the biological and geographic history of the Amazon River Basin.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ichthyology collection, which currently houses nearly 1.2 million specimens and nearly 3,000 types, is one of the most important such collections in the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department also hosts the All Catfish Species Inventory (a comprehensive online resource on catfish) and Catfish Bones (an online digital atlas of catfish morphology), and is a participant in Neodat II (an online resource of Neotropic ichthyology collections).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the early members of the Academy, Thomas Say and Isaac Lea, were malacologists (see also conchologists).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tucker Abbott, Samuel Stehman Haldeman, Henry A.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tryon, Jr. were other noted malacologists who worked at the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's malacology collection is the oldest such collection in the United States and is the 3rd largest in the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It currently contains over 10 million specimens, including types erected by more than 400 authors.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Gary Rosenberg, an expert on Jamaican land snails, is a leader in digitised museum collections and research data.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research websites include the Malacology Georeferencing Project an online database of Western Atlantic Marine Mollusca (Malacolog) Archived September 24, 2015, at the Wayback Machine, and the OBIS Indo-Pacific Mollusc database.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research associate and former curator Danielle Graf, an expert on Unionidae (freshwater mussels), maintains the MUSSEL Project web site.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The majority of ornithologists active in the United States during the first half of the 19th century, including Charles Lucien Bonaparte, George Ord, Titian Ramsay Peale, John James Audubon, John Cassin, Thomas Nuttall, and John Kirk Townsend, were active members of the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later notable Academy ornithologists include James Bond, Frank Gill, Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee, Pete Myers, Fred Sheldon, and Witmer Stone.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] With nearly 200,000 specimens representing over 9,000 species, the Ornithology collection is one of the largest and most taxonomically complete bird collections in the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Delaware Valley Ornithological Club (DVOC) has held regular meetings at the Academy since 1890.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Vertebrate paleontology in the United States originated in Philadelphia through the efforts of naturalists and scientists associated with the American Philosophical Society (APS) during the first decade of the 19th century and at The Academy of Natural Sciences thereafter.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] By the end of the 19th century, the holdings from the APS, including the Thomas Jefferson Fossil Collection, had been transferred to the Academy for safekeeping.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, the collection contains more than 22,000 specimens, including many types.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Richard Harlan was an early member who introduced many American naturalists to the groundbreaking works of Georges Cuvier.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Joseph Leidy, who described *Hadrosaurus* and alerted the scientific world to the paleontological treasures of the American West, is considered the "father" of American vertebrate paleontology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Edward Drinker Cope, who also worked extensively on other vertebrates, is best known for his rivalry with Othniel Charles Marsh during the infamous Bone Wars.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Daeschler is currently studying the evolution of Devonian tetrapods, but he will be retiring in September 2023.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] He is a co-discoverer of the transitional "fishapod" *Tiktaalik roseae* from the Canadian Arctic and the discoverer of two tetrapods, *Hynerpeton* and *Densignathus* from the Catskill Formation in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy houses several collections of smaller size yet historical and scientific importance.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The general invertebrate collection contains about 22,600 specimens, while the invertebrate paleontology collection contains about 105,000 lots.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Generally, 21,500 specimens are gaunt, 13,500 are affiliated skins, and 1,700 are wet-preserved specimens.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Myers Rotifer Collection is the most comprehensive collection of rotifers on microslides.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herpetology collection contains about 40,000 specimens, including more than 500 type specimens.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The mammalogy collection contains about 36,000 specimens and 180 holotypes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Among the naturalists and scientists associated with these collections are Timothy Conrad, Edward Drinker Cope, Richard Harlan, John Edwards Holbrook, William W.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, Henry Charles Lea, Isaac Lea, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, and Thomas Say.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Formerly the Limnology Department, the Patrick Center for Environmental Research focuses on applied ecology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Founded in 1947 by Ruth Patrick, formerly of the Diatom Herbarium, it was one of the earliest U.S. environmental consulting concerns.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its attachment to the Academy led it to become the first to employ interdisciplinary teams of scientists to study freshwater systems and the first to regard biodiversity as a central criterion of water quality.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its 1948 biological survey of the Conestoga River Basin in Pennsylvania, a milestone in environmental research, led to similar surveys and studies throughout much of the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Characteristically, these earlier projects were joint projects of the Limnology Department and private industry.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since the rise of the environmental movement in the 1960s and 1970s and the resulting increases in governmental regulation of water pollution, the environmental assessments pioneered at the Academy are increasingly conducted by private environmental consulting firms.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of the work employs most of the center's expertise and capabilities, such as recent studies on the ecological effects of small dams or the ecological benefits of riparian reforestation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other studies may involve only one or a couple of the research programs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a current project sampling sediment cores in tidal marshes throughout the Delaware Estuary.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This undertaking, possibly the most comprehensive core sampling in any estuary, relies extensively on the center's expertise in biogeochemistry and phycology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Once the sampling is completed, scientist will be able to investigate historical trends in marsh development, carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus cycling, water pollution, salinity variations, and climatic change by analysing the core's sediments, chemistry, and diatom assemblages.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Biogeochemistry Section of the Patrick Center is concerned with the influence of aquatic organisms on the sources, fate and transport of chemicals in aquatic systems.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies frequently deal with the carbon and nutrient cycling as well as those of trace elements (e.g., lead, copper, mercury, and zinc) and organic contaminants such as polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The section regularly provides water, sediment and tissue analyses for government, intergovernmental agencies, and private companies from around the country.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to the sediment core project mentioned above, it has recently studied the effects of small dams on sediment contaminants, photochemical transformation of marsh-derived dissolved organic matter, and sedimentation and eutrophication in salt marshes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ecological Modeling Section employs sophisticated and rigorous mathematical modelling techniques to address a variety of questions in basic and applied research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Examples include watershed-scale modeling and risk assessment; nonlinear population models structured by age, body size, or space; particle transport in turbulent aquatic systems; and the ecology and control of exotic invasive plants in urban parks.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Fisheries Section of the Patrick Center conducts research into the ecology, conservation, and management of lotic and estuarine fishes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies may range from the analysis of fish tissues for contaminants, monitoring fish populations for environmental assessments, to investigating the life histories of individual species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Benthic macroinvertebrates (primarily aquatic insects, crustaceans, and mollusks) are useful for biological monitoring programs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Their varied life spans, ranging from weeks to years, are long enough to reveal intermittent and continuous pollutants, yet short enough respond to worsening or improving water quality.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Macroinvertebrate Section at the Patrick Center has extensive experience in bioassessment, biomonitoring, and inventorying of freshwater habitats throughout the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Because of their great diversity and specific ecological requirements, algae, particularly diatoms, make excellent indicators of water quality.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Moreover, diatoms are readily preserved in sediments, which make them useful organisms for studying paleolimnology (the long-term trends of streams and lakes).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Phycology Section of the Patrick Center provides algal analyses for governmental and other agencies interested in both assessing water quality and long-term environmental trends.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] One such undertaking is the analyses of diatom assemblages in lake sediments (sediment cores) throughout the eastern United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This work, part of a large project managed by the EPA, will try to establish reference (pre-anthropogenic) conditions for lakes throughout the country.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to these research efforts, the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center has developed a set of online resources Archived September 6, 2019, at the Wayback Machine for using algae in environmental research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These include an algal image database, autecology datasets for freshwater algae, algae research with the USGS National Water-Quality Assessment (NAWQA) program, and a diatom paleolimnology database.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] For most of its history, biological taxonomy and systematics were conducted using comparative morphology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, however, advances in molecular biology and computational technologies have opened new possibilities for studying the diversity and history of life through the use of cladistics and computational phylogenetics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These technologies also offer new opportunities for molecular ecology and conservation genetics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy scientists have been early adapters of molecular biology techniques.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Allozymes, DNA-DNA hybridization, immunoelectrophoresis, restriction site analyses of mitochondrial DNA and serology were used extensively since the late 1960s.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent molecular work mainly employs DNA sequencing, microsatellites, and AFLP (amplified fragment length polymorphism).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2004, the Laboratory for Molecular Systematics and Ecology (LMSE) was formed as a shared, multi-user facility to improve access to and provide training for the use of molecular data in systematic and ecological research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to supporting staff, the lab offers research opportunities for students and post-doctoral fellowships.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's work in Mongolia started with the realization of the unique research opportunities available at Lake Hovsgol (Hovsgol Nuur).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This large lake and its watershed were remarkably pristine and relatively unknown, especially in comparison to its sister lake in Russia, Lake Baikal.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, a multidisciplinary team of scientists from the Academy, as well as from other American institutions, Mongolia, Russia, and Japan started a multi-year study of the lake's biodiversity, limnology, and watershed.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Although this research was scientifically rewarding, it was apparent that issues concerning environmental protection and sustainable economic development needed addressing.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Consequently, work at Hovsgol shifted to ecosystem studies and capacity building.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] One early undertaking was the enhancement of the operational and physical infrastructure at Hovsgol National Park.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Long-term ecological monitoring of several tributary watersheds began in 1997 and soon the site would be adopted into the International Long Term Ecological Research Network.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent work at Hovsgol is focusing on the consequences of and sustainable responses to climate change.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The region lies in a transitional zone between the semi-arid Eurasian Steppe (grasslands) to the south and the Eurasian Taiga (boreal forest) to the north.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] As such, it is an ideal mid-continental site at which to monitor the ecological effects of climate change.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, changes in livestock herding practices raise concerns about overgrazing and desertification.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In response, the team at Hovsgol created and distributed a *Herder Handbook* and continues to conduct research and work with nomadic herders to develop sustainable practices.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey is a multi-year biodiversity survey, environmental monitoring and capacity building project managed by Jon Gelhaus of the Academy's Entomology Department.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] A total of 217 sites from the Selenge River Basin, the most populous and most extensive drainage in Mongolia, were surveyed from 2003 to 2006.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Most of these sites are in rivers or streams, but some are in freshwater and saltwater lakes, hot and cold springs, and marsh wetlands.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Additional sites from the remote drainage systems in western Mongolia will be sampled in 2008.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The survey has yielded numerous new species and hundreds of geographic records for known aquatic insects, provided an extensive dataset for ongoing environmental monitoring, and has helped develop research and technical infrastructures in Mongolia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This capacity building includes, in collaboration with the Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology, the building of the first research laboratory in Mongolia dedicated to the study of aquatic invertebrates.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also includes training of Mongolian scientists and students.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Center for Environmental Policy informs and engages various constituents, promotes solutions, and builds public and professional awareness on important environmental topics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Much of its activities focus on public programs and working groups.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center hosts or participates in a number of public programs that are free and open to the public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Urban Sustainability Forums feature panels of local and national experts discussing environmental and sustainability topics as they relate to the Philadelphia region.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Town Square, which may feature a panel or an individual, addresses a variety of topics relating to the environment or public science.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center also hosts candidate forums, conferences and workshops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center acts as a logistical hub for a number of Working Groups organized around sustainability issues.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently active groups include one for condominium and building co-op owners, a network of faith-based environmental groups, and a forum of senior executives in the private sector.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Library and Archives were established at the Academy's founding meeting in 1812 for the purpose of supporting its natural science research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library provides online access, services, collections, imaging, and shared resources with other libraries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library houses nearly 200,000 volumes ranging from works published in the 16th century to current journals and books.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its holdings also include illustrated works from as early as the 15th century, including Konrad Gessner's *Historia animalium*, Maria Sibylla Merian's *Insects of Surinam*, Edward Lear's *Psittacidae or Parrots*, and a double elephant folio of John James Audubon's *The Birds of America*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences* was the first peer-reviewed publication in the United States devoted to the natural sciences.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1842, it had been superseded by the *Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Proceedings* have been published continuously since 1841.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal* was reborn in 1847 as a larger-format publication that could accommodate longer articles and monographs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy publishes three other series.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The occasional series *Notulae Naturae* began in 1939 as a means to quickly publish short items, usually not longer than 16 pages on subject areas such as zoology, botany, ecology, geology and paleontology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Monographs* series, which began in 1935, is composed principally of larger systematic reviews of selected taxonomic groups.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Special Publications* series, begun in 1922, includes works such as biography, taxonomy, historical reviews, and collections surveys.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO (VIsual REsource for Ornithology) is the most comprehensive collection of bird images in the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Started in 1979, the collection contains over 180,000 photographs representing over 7,300 species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The collection contains work by some of the world's most talented photographers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO licenses bird images for a wide variety of commercial and non-profit uses.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy first opened its collections to the public in 1828.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The popularity of its exhibits soared in 1868 with the debut of the world's first mounted dinosaur skeleton, *Hadrosaurus*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The size of the crowds flocking to this display prompted the Academy to relocate to its present-and roomier-location in 1876.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] As with most museums in the 19th century, there was little separation of the Academy's collections, which were vital to scientific work, and the public spaces.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Not only did this subject the collections to extra wear and tear, but visitors were typically confronted with a bewildering assemblage of specimens with little in the way of supplemental information.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Over time, however, museums such as the Academy started to showcase their more popular specimens while sequestering the bulk of the collections.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, they spent more effort interpreting their public displays.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Museums started to play a more active role in educating the public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] One expression of this transformation was the rise of that icon of natural history museums, the diorama.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These three-dimensional displays were the virtual reality of their time, providing generations of museum visitors with their only opportunity to experience distant places and exotic wildlife.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green created The Academy's first diorama, depicting rocky mountain goats.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green's work was at first controversial amongst The Academy's staff, due to both the cost and accusations of sensationalism, but proved popular amongst the public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1935, the Works Progress Administration began providing artists to help work on the dioramas, fueling the exhibits' continued expansion.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] By presenting the wilderness to the public, dioramas nurtured an appreciation of our natural heritage, which, coincided with the growth of the Conservation Movement in the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy currently has 37 dioramas, most of which were installed in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] They feature a variety of animals from Africa, Asia, and North America.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of these, such as the caribou, lion, and plains zebra are familiar and relatively common, but others, such as the desert bighorn, kiang, Kodiak bear, panda, and passenger pigeon, are threatened, endangered, or extinct.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2018, under the management of Drexel University, The Academy renovated some of the older dioramas.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] These renovations were meant to increase the scientific accuracy of the displays and improve their aesthetics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Another icon of natural history museums is the dinosaur skeleton.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The first of these, the *Hadrosaurus* mount created by noted natural history artist Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins, made its debut at the Academy in 1868.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] *Hadrosaurus* mounts also found their way into other public venues, including Princeton University, the Royal Scottish Museum, the Smithsonian, and the 1876 American Centennial Exposition.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] A special exhibit on the history of *Hadrosaurus foulkii* ran from November 22, 2008 to April 19, 2009.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] A skeletal mount of a related dinosaur, *Corythosaurus*, served as the centerpiece of the Academy's "Hall of Earth History" during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1986, the Academy opened a new exhibit, "Discovering Dinosaurs".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This was the first large-scale exhibit to incorporate the findings of the "dinosaur renaissance".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Instead of cold-blooded and lumbering reptiles, dinosaurs were conceived as active-and possibly warm-blooded-animals more akin to birds than reptiles.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, another type of dinosaur was the subject of an exhibition at the academy when it featured Jim Gary's Twentieth Century Dinosaurs and found that it was an enormous success with the public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, the academy also opened "Outside-In", a hands-on children's nature museum.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, it pioneered the hands-on simulation of a dinosaur dig, with its "The Big Dig".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other permanent exhibits include "Secrets of the Diorama", an insight into what goes into a diorama, and "Science at the Academy", which showcases current Academy research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also has special, changing exhibits.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent changing exhibits include "Skin: Living Armor, Evolving Identity", "Illuminating Birds", "Extreme Deep: Mission to the Abyss", and "Crocs: Ancient Predators in a Modern World".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Four weekend festivals organized around scientific disciplines, are held during the year.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Paleopalooza, held in mid-February, features fossil collections and talks by leading paleontologists.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Earth Day Festival, held in mid-April, features scientists from the Academy's Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Bug Fest, held in mid August, features entomologists, insect collections and live insects.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Philadelphia Shell Show, held in mid-October, features an international shell market and competitive shell displays.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy began offering lectures to the public as early as the 1820s.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Current offerings include natural history author talks, lectures by scientists, workshops and classes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, the Center for Environmental Policy produces public programs on environmental issues.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its Nature Club in the 1930s, the Academy has offered programming just for children.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Several programs appropriate for different age groups are currently offered.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Safari Overnight sleepovers (camp-ins) are held on selected weekends during Fall, Winter, and Spring.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts can participate in day workshops and sleepovers to fulfill badge and pin requirements.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tiny Tot Explorers is a program for toddlers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] A new series of Family Workshops designed for both adults and children was launched in early 2010.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Wild Weekends", held on selected weekends throughout the year, offer a variety of children's programs, including hands-on exploration of museum specimens, crafts and live animal shows with mammals, birds and reptiles.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Live animal shows are also presented at regular times on other days and featured prominently in the educational programs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Field trips to the Academy are available throughout the year for schools, summer camps and other groups.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Optional directed programs include Discovery Lessons for younger age groups (pre-K and higher) and Science Explorers for older children (grades 7 through 9).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Academy on the Go" is an educational outreach program that visits schools, camps, and community centers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] WINS (Women in Natural Sciences) is an innovative and successful science enrichment program conducted by The Academy of Natural Sciences in collaboration with the School District of Philadelphia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its founding in 1982, WINS has been providing female public school students with hands-on science classes, scientific literacy and skill-building activities, and opportunities for personal growth in a uniquely nurturing setting.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy Explorers Camp is a day camp program offered during Spring Break and the Summer.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The George Washington Carver Science Fair is held in February or March.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Science fair participants are eligible for the George Washington Carver Scholars summer program, which is also held at the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Educator workshops are held throughout the year.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The most recent series covered the integration of science and literacy skills.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Self-guided workbooks tailored for younger children are available for some of the museum exhibits.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Hayden Memorial Geological Award is given to prominent scientists working in geology or paleontology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1888 in memory of Ferdinand V.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Hayden, a distinguished American geologist and pioneering surveyor of the American West who had extensive ties to the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Established in 1980, the Gold Medal for Distinction in Natural History Art is awarded to people whose artistic endeavors and life's work have contributed to our understanding and appreciation of living things.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Richard Hopper Day Memorial Medal, established in 1960 by his granddaughter, Margaret Day Dilks, is awarded in recognition of outstanding contributions in interpreting the natural sciences to the public.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Joseph Leidy Award honors research in the natural sciences.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1923 as a tribute to the many contributions and long association of Joseph Leidy with the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Böhlke Memorial Endowment Fund honors the memory of James E.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke who were prominent ichthyologists at the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] This fund provides support for graduate students and recent postdoctoral researchers to work with the Ichthyology Collection and the Academy's Library.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Gallagher Fellowship provides a unique opportunity for original, multi-year, postdoctoral or sabbatical research on the systematics of microscopic invertebrates, especially Rotifera.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The research focus must be on systematics and may employ ecological, behavioral, physiological, molecular or developmental tools.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jessup and McHenry Awards are competitively awarded to students wishing to conduct studies at the postgraduate, doctoral and postdoctoral levels under the supervision or sponsorship of a member of the curatorial staff of the Academy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Jessup Award is given for any specialty in which our curators have expertise.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The McHenry Fund is restricted to botanists.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Eckelberry Endowment helps support the efforts of wildlife painters, sculptors, printmakers, and other artists to better acquaint themselves with the natural world through both museum and field research.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, artistic and scientific mentors counsel and assist these artists as their careers develop.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] An **academy of sciences** is a type of learned society or academy (as special scientific institution) dedicated to sciences that may or may not be state funded.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Some state funded academies are national, or royal (i.e.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] United Kingdom's Royal Society of London for Improving Natural Knowledge) as a form of honor.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] The other type of academies are *Academy of Arts* or combination of both (e.g., American Academy of Arts and Sciences).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] *Academy of Letters* is another related expression, encompassing literature.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] In non-English-speaking countries, the range of academic fields of the members of a national Academy of Science often includes scholarly disciplines which would not normally be classed as "science" in English.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Many languages use a broad term for systematized learning which includes both natural sciences and social sciences and fields such as literary studies, linguistics, history, or art history.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] As the engineering sciences have become more varied and advanced, there is a recent trend in many advanced countries to organize the National Academy of Engineering (or National Academy of Engineering Sciences), separate from the national academy of sciences.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Academies of science play an important role in science diplomacy efforts.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Academies are increasingly organized in regional or even international academies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] The Interacademy Partnership for example is a global network consisting of over 140 national, regional and global member academies of science, engineering and medicine.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Pan-Europe academies include the Academia Europaea and the European Academy of Sciences and Arts.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Additionally, there are many regional associations such as ALLEA in Europe, NASAC as the Network of African Science Academies, IANAS in Latin America, and AASSA in Asia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] The International Science Council brings together international scientific unions and associations as well as national and regional scientific organizations such as academies and research councils from the natural sciences, social sciences and the humanities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Apart from national academies of science, there are now increasingly also national young academies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] National young academies usually select members for a limited term, normally 4–5 years, after which members become academy alumni.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Young academies typically engage with issues important to young scientists.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] These include, for example, science education or the dialog between science and society.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Most young academies are affiliated with a senior Academy of Sciences or with a network of senior academies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] The Global Young Academy, which itself is a science academy (e.g. full member of Interacademy Partnership) often serves as a facilitator of the growing global network of young academies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] Since its creation, more than 35 national young academies have been established.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/academy-of-sciences] In 2019, there were 41 national young academies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The **Acoustical Society of America** (**ASA**) is an international scientific society founded in 1929 dedicated to generating, disseminating and promoting the knowledge of acoustics and its practical applications.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The Society is primarily a voluntary organization of about 7500 members and attracts the interest, commitment, and service of many professionals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Watson and Wallace Waterfall (1900–1974), a former doctoral student of Watson, were invited by UCLA's Vern Oliver Knudsen to an evening dinner at Knudsen's beach club in Santa Monica.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The three physicists decided to form a society of acoustical engineers interested in architectural acoustics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] In the early part of December 1928, Wallace Waterfall sent letters to sixteen people inquiring about the possibility of organizing such a society.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Harvey Fletcher offered the use of the Bell Telephone Laboratories at 463 West Street in Manhattan as a meeting place for an organizational, initial meeting to be held on December 27, 1928.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The meeting was attended by forty scientists and engineers who started the Acoustical Society of America (ASA).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Temporary officers were elected: Harvey Fletcher as president, V.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Knudsen as vice-president, Wallace Waterfall as secretary, and Charles Fuller Stoddard (1876–1958) as treasurer.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] A constitution and by-laws were drafted.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The first issue of the *Journal of the Acoustical Society of America* was published in October 1929.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The Society has 13 technical committees that represent specialized interests in the field of acoustics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The committees organize technical sessions at conferences and are responsible for the representation of their sub-field in ASA publications.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The first meeting was attended by forty scientists and engineers who started the Acoustical Society of America (ASA).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The Acoustical Society of America publishes a wide variety of material related to the knowledge and practical application of acoustics in physics, engineering, architecture, noise, oceanography, biology, speech and hearing, psychology and music.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] In 2021, the ASA Publications' Office began producing *Across Acoustics,* a podcast to highlight authors' research from these four publications.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The ASA presents awards and prizes to individuals for contributions to the field of Acoustics.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Most technical committees also sponsor awards for best student or early career presenter at each conference.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The ASA offers membership and conference attendance to students at a substantially reduced rate.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] Conference attendance is further promoted by travel subsidies and formal and informal student meetings and social activities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/acoustical-society-of-america] The ASA also expanded services to students in 2004 by introducing regional student chapters.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
